camelCase(...) bug in v4.10.0
body:
In v4.10.0 `_.camelCase(..)` doesn't return the same value as in v4.6.1.
Example:

``` js
_.camelCase('MICs'); // becomes "miCs" in 4.10.0
_.camelCase('MICs'); // becomes "mics" in 4.6.1
```

As I didn't find any change about that in the changelog, I guess this is a bug?

title: Why do "By" functions only provide a single param to iteratees?
body:
According to the changelog in Lodash v4:

> Made “By” methods like _.groupBy & _.sortBy provide a single param to iteratees

I'm curious about the reason to ditch the other params that were provided to iteratees in previous versions of Lodash. Especially for the `key|index` parameter, there are some valid use-cases for using it (for instance when you'd like to turn an Object into an Array, where the Array order is determined by the keys of the provided Object).

title: Make sum/sumBy return 0 on empty array
body:
``` js
const items = getItems();
const totalScore = _.sumBy(items, 'score');
```

`totalScore` will be either a number, or in the case of empty arrays, `undefined`. This has bitten us more than once.
I feel that since `sum` and `sumBy` are geared toward numerics, it makes since to just return the number 0 for empty input.

(doing string concatenation with it is technically possible, but doesn't make a lot of sense given `Array.prototype.join`)

Similar to #1838, but strictly regarding an empty array (unsure why it was marked invalid).

title: Feature request: fp.assign should have arguments reversed
body:
## Use case

Using `fp.assign` to create helper functions which assign key/value pairs to objects, e.g. `assignFoo` which assigns the `foo` field of an object to `'bar'`:

```
> var assignFoo = fp.assign({foo: 'bar'})
```
### Expected/desired behavior

Being able to use partial function in compositions to assign desired value to new objects: `readJSON('foo.json').then(assignFoo);`
### Actual/current behavior

Partial function returned by `fp.assign` assigns 2nd argument to the first, not the other way around.  In this case, `assignFoo` actually assigns its argument to `{foo: 'bar'}`:

```
> assignFoo({baz: 'buz'})
{ foo: 'bar', baz: 'buz' }
> assignFoo({foo: 'baz'})
{ foo: 'baz' }
```

title: run scripts synchronous in foreground
body:
PR #2177 made the use of background scripts safer by introducing `wait` to ensure all background tasks finish before continuing, but I just discovered there is still an issue with background scripts: `wait` doesn't return an exit code if one of the background scripts fails. EG,

``` bash
cmartin:static martin$ echo 'start' && sleep 3 & exit 1 & sleep 2 & wait && echo 'end'     
[1] 34914
[2] 34915
[3] 34916
start
[1]   Done                    echo 'start' && sleep 3
[2]-  Exit 1                  exit 1
[3]+  Done                    sleep 2
end
```

This PR changes npm scripts back to using the synchronous `&&` which only continues if the previous command is successful. As it relates to the npm scripts, this will ensure that tests only will be run on a successful build, and that the validate git hook behaves correctly. Further, I'm not sure how you manage publishing, but if you do something like `npm run validate && node some_publish_script` this would prevent you from possibly publishing unsuccessfully built code and/or code not passing tests.

Feel free to close if you're comfortable with how it is now, or if you would rather introduce a [tool](https://github.com/mysticatea/npm-run-all) to still keep this parallel. Just wanted to bring it up :)

title: _.overEvery and _.overSome may accept _.matchesProperty shortcut (and probably others)
body:
Consider the following:

``` js
_(collection)
  .filter(['some_id', someObj.id])
  .filter(['some_token', anotherObj.token])
  .filter(somePredicateFunction)
  .value();
```

might as well be written as:

``` js
_(collection)
  .filter(_.overEvery(
    _.partial(_.matchesProperty, _, ['some_id', someObj.id]),
    _.partial(_.matchesProperty, _, ['some_token', anotherObj.token]),
    somePredicateFunction
  )
  .value();
```

or for readability as:

``` js
_(collection)
  .filter(_.overEvery(
    ['some_id', someObj.id],
    ['some_token', anotherObj.token],
    somePredicateFunction
  )
  .value();
```

title: ensure all background jobs finish before continuing
body:
Multiple scripts can be run in parallel by running all but one in the background. EG, `sleep 1` runs sleep in the foreground, `sleep 2 &` runs sleep in the background, and `sleep 2 & sleep 1` runs `sleep 2` in the background and `sleep 1` in the foreground (hence, in parallel). Currently in lodash, this is being utilized for scripts that can be run in parallel, but there is a racetime condition with the script being run in the foreground.

For example `echo 'sleeps beginning' && sleep 7 & sleep 1 && echo 'sleeps finished'` demonstrates this racetime condition where the process running in the foreground finishes before the process running with it in parallel in the background.

This is not demonstrating itself currently with the scripts employing background processes because the foreground process (the last piece of the script) happens to take longer. The place where you would see it would be with `npm test` which waits for `npm run build`. If `npm run build:fp` finishes before `npm run build:main`, the testing will begin with build:main incomplete.

Using `wait` solves this problem. Eg, `echo 'sleeps beginning' && sleep 7 & sleep 1 & wait && echo 'sleeps finished'`

``` bash
cmartin:lodash martin$ time (echo 'sleeps beginning' && sleep 7 & sleep 1 & wait && echo 'sleeps finished')
sleeps beginning
sleeps finished

real    0m7.015s
user    0m0.003s
sys 0m0.006s
```

vs 

``` bash
cmartin:lodash martin$ time (echo 'sleeps beginning' && sleep 7 & sleep 1 && echo 'sleeps finished')
sleeps beginning
sleeps finished

real    0m1.011s
user    0m0.001s
sys 0m0.004s
cmartin:lodash martin$ ps aux | grep sleep
martin         15895   0.0  0.0  2423356    196 s002  R+    2:03PM   0:00.00 grep sleep
martin         15893   0.0  0.0  2432752    512 s002  S     2:03PM   0:00.00 sleep 7
```

title: Wrong Sorting by _.orderBy of insensitive string values
Suggestions for the Documentation
body:
There's a tremendous amount of methods in lodash/underscore. The documentation is getting hard to navigate. I think funcy's documentation (for python) is more navigable due to the organization into sequences/collections as well as sub-dividing each section into the purpose I'm looking for (unite, transform, select, etc).

I know there is a difference between Arrays, Collections, and Objects but from a usability standpoint it's hard to navigate because it means I have to look in different sections most of the time if I do not find what I want. For Collections and Objects I have to check both in order to find what I want. For Arrays I need to check all three and not all collections or object functions work on arrays as the name implies. I think it would be useful to merge collections and objects into a single section or find some way of allowing filters for what works with the object type.

Real example:
Before I found _.omit today (the first word that came to mind was 'without' but _.without acts only on Arrays) I thought to use _.reject (in collections section) with a iterator using _.has. This was not a pleasant searching experience. I originally thought of 'contains' or even using _.find because _.has was not in the top two sections. I finally found _.has after reading every function name from the top. It's a long read. It turns out _.has also works for arrays. Given that _.has is all the way down in the objects section it means that if I were to look for that behavior for an array I may not find it for quite a while.

Another improvement for the documentation would be the grouping or hiding of variations of the same function in the list (_.[command]By, [command]With, [command]Right, etc. etc.)

title: _.isEmpty returns incorrect result with Sets
body:
``` js
var s = new Set();

_.isEmpty(s) // => true (as expected)

s.add('value');

_.isEmpty(s) // => true, even though the set is no longer empty
```

Even though a Set's keys aren't enumerable, the behavior is somewhat unintuitive because an "empty set" is typically defined as "a set with no elements".

title: Proposal: More logic functions -- ifElse/when/unless
body:
Since we now have `_.cond` it might be good to add more logic functions. These would be particularly useful for people using `lodash/fp`.

I would propose the following:
- `_.ifElse(predicate, onTrue, onFalse, value)`
- `_.when(predicate, onTrue, value)`
- `_.unless(predicate, onFalse, value)`

`when`/`unless` return the result of calling `onTrue`/`onFalse` with `value` if the predicate is met/not-met, otherwise `value` is returned untouched.

title: Proposal: _.meanBy
body:
Similar to `_.minBy`, `_.maxBy` & `_.sumBy`, seems fitting to include a `_.meanBy`.
I've implemented a solution using `_.sumBy(array, [iteratee]) / array.length`.
